# BusyBox

BusyBox combines small implementations of many common Unix utilities into a
single executable.  The same binary can behave as `cp`, `sed`, `tar`, `init`,
`ash`, and many other commands, depending on how it is invoked.

The project is designed for systems where size, memory use, and simple
deployment matter: embedded Linux systems, initramfs images, rescue media,
installers, containers, and other constrained environments.  BusyBox applets
usually implement the most useful behavior of their larger counterparts rather
than every available option.

BusyBox is distributed under GPLv2 only.  See `LICENSE` for the full license
text.


## Quick Start

The build system follows the same general pattern as the Linux kernel:

```
make defconfig
make
./busybox --help
```

To choose a smaller or more specialized set of applets and features, configure
the tree before building:

```
make menuconfig
make
```

If `menuconfig` is not available on your system, use:

```
make config
```

For the full list of build and configuration targets, run:

```
make help
```

More detailed build and installation notes are in `INSTALL`.


## Using BusyBox

BusyBox chooses which applet to run from the command name used to start it.
For example, if the BusyBox binary is linked as `ls`, running `ls` starts the
BusyBox implementation of `ls`.

You can also invoke applets directly through the `busybox` command:

```
./busybox ls -l /proc
./busybox cat LICENSE
```

Running `./busybox` with no applet name prints the applets compiled into the
current binary.


## Installing

After building, install BusyBox and its applet links with:

```
make install
```

The install target uses `CONFIG_PREFIX` to decide where links are created:

```
make CONFIG_PREFIX=/path/from/root install
```

The build generates `busybox.links`, which lists the enabled applets and their
install paths.  Depending on configuration, installation creates symlinks or
hardlinks to the BusyBox binary.  You can also run the install helper directly:

```
applets/install.sh
```


## Configuration Notes

BusyBox is highly configurable.  Common starting points are:

- `make allnoconfig` - disable everything and add only what you need.
- `make defconfig` - enable a broad, general-purpose configuration.
- `make allyesconfig` - enable almost everything, including options mainly
  useful for testing.
- `make randconfig` - generate a random configuration for build testing.

The resulting configuration is stored in `.config`.  To update an older
configuration for a newer source tree, run:

```
make oldconfig
```

The `configs/` directory contains additional target-specific defconfig files.


## Testing

The regular test suite can be run with:

```
make check
```

Unit tests are built as a BusyBox applet when `CONFIG_UNIT_TEST` is enabled.
They can be run directly with:

```
./busybox unit
```

See `docs/unit-tests.txt` for details on writing and running unit tests.


## Source Layout

- `applets/` - applet registration and generated applet metadata.
- `archival/`, `coreutils/`, `findutils/`, `networking/`, `shell/`, and similar
  directories - applet implementations grouped by domain.
- `include/` - shared headers.
- `libbb/` - shared BusyBox support library.
- `scripts/` - build, configuration, and maintenance helpers.
- `testsuite/` - functional tests.
- `docs/` - project documentation, style notes, applet guidance, and topic
  references.


## Contributing

Before making a substantial change, read:

- `docs/contributing.txt`
- `docs/style-guide.txt`
- `docs/new-applet-HOWTO.txt`, when adding a new applet

For applet changes, check the relevant `.c` file for maintainers or authors
and consider discussing larger work on the mailing list before writing a large
patch.

Bug reports and patches are most useful when they include:

- The BusyBox version or commit.
- The build configuration, especially relevant `.config` settings.
- The platform, kernel, C library, and compiler.
- A short shell transcript that reproduces the problem.
- Expected behavior, preferably with a comparison to the relevant standard or
  another implementation.


